\begin{parts}
    \item The table shows the areas, in km$^2$, of the four largest rainforests in the world.

    \begin{InsertScreenShot}
        \begin{tabularx}{0.8\textwidth}{|l|r|}
        \hline
        Rainforest & Area (km$^2$) \\
        \hline
        Amazon & 5\,500\,000 \\
        \hline
        Congo & 2\,000\,000 \\
        \hline
        Atlantic & 1\,315\,000 \\
        \hline
        Valdivian & 250\,000 \\
        \hline
        \end{tabularx}
    \end{InsertScreenShot}

    \begin{subparts}
        \item Find the area of the Valdivian rainforest as a percentage of the area of the Amazon rainforest.

        \AnswerLine[][\%]
        \Marks{1}

        \item Write, in its simplest form, the ratio of the areas of the rainforests Valdivian : Atlantic : Congo.

        \AnswerLine[] : \AnswerLine[] : \AnswerLine[]
        \Marks{2}

        \item The Amazon rainforest has 60\% of its area in Brazil and 10\% of its area in Colombia. \\
        $\dfrac{1}{43}$\% of the remaining area of the rainforest is in Peru. \\
        Find the percentage of the Amazon rainforest that is in Brazil, Colombia and Peru.

        \AnswerLine[][\%]
        \Marks{3}

        \item The area of the Amazon rainforest represents $\dfrac{27}{50}$ of the total area of rainforest in the world. \\
        Calculate the total area of rainforest in the world. \\
        Give your answer correct to the nearest 100\,000 km$^2$.

        \AnswerLine[][km$^2$]
        \Marks{3}

        \item In the world, 60.7 hectares of rainforest are lost every minute. \\
        Calculate the total area, in hectares, of rainforest that is lost in 365 days. \\
        Give your answer in standard form.

        \AnswerLine[][]
        \Marks{3}
    \end{subparts}

    \item The Amazon river has a length of 6440 km, correct to the nearest 10 km. \\
    The Congo river has a length of 4400 km, correct to the nearest 100 km. \\
    Calculate the upper bound of the difference between the lengths of the Amazon river and the Congo river.

    \AnswerLine[][km]
    \Marks{3}
\end{parts}

